<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Voice realism: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">judged on long-form narration rather than short demo clips, since most tools sound convincing for one sentence but start cracking by the third paragraph</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Pricing clarity: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">measured by real cost per finished minute of audio rather than the headline number on the homepage, since credit systems and character billing make sticker prices misleading on their own</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Commercial licensing: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">given extra scrutiny, since a platform that locks commercial use behind a $250-a-year tier is not actually a free option even if the homepage advertises one</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Language and accent coverage: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">checked across each platform&#8217;s full supported list, not just the flagship voices shown in marketing</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Creator control:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> evaluated on how much influence users actually get over pitch, pacing, emotion, and final output rather than just picking a preset voice</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Free tiers were tested directly rather than judged from marketing pages, and every entry on this list states clearly where commercial rights actually begin.</span></p>
